div.div:
A "difference embedded in a similarity" is useful to identify differences like "trivial differences between similar types". This is useful where the similarity enables the difference, such as where the similarity acts like an interface which can support other variables. Relatedly, it's useful for workflows like 'change a base solution' (change a structure into the other similar structure, which is slightly different in a way that could be useful.
Because of the common 'shape' interface that forms the similarity, these shapes can be easily compared and differentiated.

div.div: Both of these different structures have a common structure of a "pair of vectors joined at a common endpoint (forming an angle)" in common forming the similarity, so comparing these on the shape interface or the angle interface or corner interface is possible. Similarly, the 'vector set forming an angle' can be used to generate the cube in other ways as well, such as by connecting other vector pairs forming the sides or by applying rotations to squares formed by vector pairs. If they had noticeably different magnitudes, comparing them that way could be useful as well.

div.div:
At some points in this interim space, these embeddings will overlap/connect/intersect or otherwise appear ambiguously similar, and will eventually reach the other side.
These 'similarities in differences' and other similarity-difference structures act differently across systems, depending on variables like how 'abstract' the similarity is and how it otherwise interacts with interface structures, so a rule for handling a 'difference in a similarity' might not always apply across every system containing such a structure, but these structures decompose so many other structures that they're still useful to apply, if only to identify what isn't covered by these structures which require other interfaces to identify.
This variation across systems is because similarities/differences are very abstract objects, and so while it is clear that there are multiple variations of a 'similarity in a difference' like an 'overlap' structure, there may be a system that is so well-defined as in only defining unique/maximally different structures or abstracted (such as by solving the 'overlap' problem by identifying the common type and the variables of the differences) that no overlaps occur
